snippet.textDisplay:
Of course, everyone knows that a show that was cut down too soon, was Firefly. But while we are talking Tv shows, I think it would be just a travisty to not even mention all the animes that have been killed after a season or two, despite how good they are.
Because the sad thing is, It's never about quality. It's about views. And half the time its the networks fault that these shows dont get the views that they deserve, either with little to no advertising, bad advertising or simply putting them in terrible time slots. That was one of the problems with firefly.


As for shows that went on for far too long, three examples come to mind. These three examples being some of my favourite tv shows ever. Misfits, Heroes and Doctor who.


Misfits (spoilers) has the perfect ending point after season 4. While most would say that season 2 is the end, with the best character leaving, I would say that the storylines of seasons 3 and 4 are worth it. Especially with the way it ends, one of them dying and the other going back in time terminator style to not only spend more time with his dead girlfriend, but to help start that relationship in the first place. It was the perfect ending, setting up the eternal cycle of love of THE best couple in the show. But it just kept going, now with only one member of the original cast, the worst character out of the bunch, just milling about with awful storylines and nothing that made the original so great.


Heroes should have just ended after season 2 with claire revealing their kind to the world, like she eventually does at the very end. Simply because the after that point in the show, the 3 best (and lets be honest, the 3 actually main) characters are constantly put in situations that keep them out of the main story, nerf their powers completely and make them completely useless. simply because they were too strong. I think the writers just didn't account for a season 3 and so they built up hero, syler and peter too fast for the overall show, but perfectly for if it were to end after season 2.


Doctor who. Well it had its ending clear. When Matt smith dies, it should have ended. Throughout the entire show its been made brutally clear that there is a limit to how many times the Doctor can regenerate. It was built up as the impending doom, infact an entire season was dedicated to bringing them to the characters death, which was literally given a date from the future. But it kept going, then he had another time he should have died. Another perfect death and a perfectly fitting ending. But it kept going.. and looking at the seasons after it, especially the latest ones, it really was not worth it and has truly shit stained the name Doctor who.


Oh, and I totally forgot about Skins. season 4, it should have ended. But ive wrote more than enough already

snippet.textDisplay: Gravity Falls is definitely my favorite example of a show that ended when it needed to. I absolutely loved it and would have kept watching it for many more seasons (and it was super successful so I'm sure Disney would have been more than happy to keep it going), but Alex Hirsch had the series planned out from the beginning and he ended it exactly where he wanted to end it. I really respect that! We wound up with two tight seasons, with just enough room to explore the characters and also get into and wrap up all the crazy plot shit. And that finale~!! So so so good. ♡

snippet.textDisplay:
My guess is there has never been an anime series you enjoyed. Because this is literally how all my favorite series have gone. I am but a simple woman, I enjoy my Naruto. I have been following that series since it pretty much started (1998, if you're curious), really getting into it in the early 2000s. And then it went on for 700 chapters which, I kid you not, include interdimensional time travelling aliens as the main antagonist for the entire series. That's just the cherry on top of the shit sundae that is the journey the storyline for this series took. Needless to say I stopped reading the manga at chapter 300 something and never picked it back up. These series get SO popular and my thought is that the publisher forces the artist/writers to continue making chapter after chapter, long after they probably would have liked their story to end. Or they're just really only good at writing about 50% of the time.


However, all that being said, I'm in the Naruto fandom too deep at this point. So my friend and I will get together occasionally and binge it while we rewrite it out loud to one another and lament for how good it COULD have been. The series actually does have a lot of great characters and character arcs, it's just disappointing that there were so many shitty characters and arcs that were chosen to override them. I can name like 5 more anime off the top of my head that ended this way and that I never finished, either.


I have a bad habit of stopping series before they end so there aren't many I have finished, anime or not. But of the ones I did finish, I thought Death Note was great (the manga) and Cowboy Bebop ended well, too (the anime). I honestly don't think I've followed any American live action, comedy/drama/sitcoms whatever till the end, so there's nothing there I can recommend. And now I will end my comment before I go past its season 7.
